* Consultations throughout the Gilbert Group conducted for the National Adaption Program of Action, Kiribati Adaption Project Phase I (KAP I) identified widespread concerns

* Water pumps/pipes are required to convey water from safe and secure sources to settlements and homes;
* Water wells require protection;
* Available water on the islands needs to be located and assessed;
* Water conservation needs to be practiced in the homes (including awareness raising);
* Sanitation needs improvement and more toilets must be constructed;
* Water conservation in piped systems;
* Rainwater harvesting is required with the installation of rainwater tanks.
* These strategies fall into three broad categories:
	* To make use of a variety of water sources;
	* To protect freshwater sources from the impact of human activities and animal wastes;
	* To conserve use of water by the community, industry and government agencies, with a need for complementary awareness-raising.
	* This National Sanitation Policy targets complementary strategies for the protection of water wells, freshwater sources, and lagoon foreshore waters through improved sanitation and the provision of toilets.
	* NWRP highlights the essential nature of freshwater for the survival of Kiribati, where freshwater is a vital, strategic natural resource on which the island communities and their economic growth is founded, and where security of supply needs to be assured.  NWRP also highlights priority issues for action, a number of which have direct bearing upon the priorities for sanitation:
	* The high rate of preventable deaths and illnesses due to water-borne diseases;
	* Contamination of fresh groundwater sources by human settlements and poor sanitation practices;
	* Inequities in the provision of services to schools, hospitals, clinics, rural, outer island and urban communities;
	* Limited community understanding of effective sanitation, responsible water use and protection, and
	* A need for enhanced water [and sanitation] education in schools.
	* This sanitation policy builds upon, and strengthens the relationship and complementary objectives of NWRP to present a comprehensive and complete sector

