6.0 CAUSALITY AND IMPACTS - LESSONS LEARNED
* The lessons learned from previous projects
* The lessons learned from previous projects
 give concise indications of the considerations that have been balanced in the preparation of this NSP and the accompanying 10-Year Implementation. Plan.  These are:
	* Local customs and traditional practices in South Tarawa have dictated a less-than-effective and a higher-cost approach to sanitation;
	* Water, sanitation and land tenure issues are interlinked;
	* Multi-dimensional projects require effective coordination;
	* Organisational and attitudinal change requires time;
	* Service improvement requires ongoing community motivation and commitment;
	* Service improvement requires sufficient human resources; and
	* Simple and least costly solutions will be the most appropriate and sustainable.
	* Other relevant lessons come from the approaches being taken by KAP and the Kiribati Urban Renewal Program Scoping Study.Donor funded projects have traditionally been designed with an approach that allows limited community involvement during project design and implementation.  Both projects indentified the need for extensive community consultation with the former study concluding â¢that past development initiatives in South Tarawa have not always adequately addressed the basic needs of communities, especially as they relate to appropriate and affordable solutions for water, sanitation, shelter and security of land tenure.â¢  A community-based approach to enable communities to fully engage in deciding their priorities, weighing the different options, appropriate levels of service in relation to costs, acceptability of the proposals, and monitoring of improvements will be essential for successful and sustainable outcomes and has been allowed for in this Policy.
	* This National Sanitation Policy and the accompanying 10-Year Sanitation Implementation Plan are built upon these strategies for community immersion in the choices for sanitation and their implementation.  Awareness raising, community health education and hygiene, environmental impact considerations feature highly in both NSP and NSIP.

7.0 PRIORITY ISSUES ADDRESSED BY THIS POLICY
* Issues to be urgently addressed include:
<\li1>
	* The high rate of preventable deaths and illnesses due to water borne diseases;
	* Contamination of freshwater sources from pollution and adverse effects of human activities and poor sanitation practices;
	* Protection of lagoon waters from pollution;
	* Impacts of climate variability and change on the sanitation approaches adopted;
	* Protection and enhancement of the natural environment;

